HOUSE BILL DRH10268-ST-8
Short Title: Local Government Audits. (Public)
Sponsors: Representative Winslow.
Referred to:
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO MODIFY THE PROCESS BY WHICH UNITS OF LOCAL GOVERNMENT,
3 PUBLIC AUTHORITIES, AND LOCAL SCHOOL ADMINISTRATIVE UNITS SELECT
4 AN ACCOUNTANT TO CONDUCT ANNUAL AUDITS; AND TO APPROPRIATE
5 FUNDS TO THE STATE AUDITOR TO ASSIST LOCAL GOVERNMENTS WITH
6 FINANCIAL RECORD KEEPING.
7 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
8 SECTION 1. G.S. 159-34 reads as rewritten:
9 "§ 159-34. Annual independent audit; rules and regulations.
10 (a) Each unit of local government and public authority shall have its accounts audited as
11 soon as possible after the close of each fiscal year by a certified public accountant or by an
12 accountant certified by the Commission as qualified to audit local government accounts. State
13 Auditor in accordance with subsection (b1) of this section. When specified by the secretary, the
14 audit shall evaluate the performance of a unit of local government or public authority with regard
15 to compliance with all applicable federal and State agency regulations. This audit, combined with
16 the audit of financial accounts, shall be deemed to be the single audit described by the "Federal
17 Single Audit Act of 1984".
18 (a1) The auditor shall be selected by and shall report directly to the governing board.board,
19 but in no instance may the governing board select an auditor not certified by the State Auditor as
20 qualified to audit the accounts of units of local government or public authorities. The governing
21 board shall solicit sealed bids for conducting the audit, which may be done annually but at least
22 once every five years. The governing board shall select an auditor from those sealed bids based
23 solely on cost, expertise, and time for completion of the audit and without information as to
24 identity of the bidder. If upon opening that sealed bid, the governing board determines that the
25 auditor cannot meet the audit schedule of the governing board or has performed inadequately on
26 a prior audit of the governing board, the governing board may reject that sealed bid and solicit
27 sealed bids again in accordance with this subsection.
28 (a2) The audit contract or agreement shall be comply with all of the following:
29 (i)(1) Be in writing, include writing.
30 (ii)(2) Include the entire entity in the scope of the audit, except that an audit for
31 purposes other than the annual audit required by this section should include
32 an accurate description of the scope of the audit, require audit.
33 (iii)(3) Require that a typewritten or printed report on the audit be prepared as set
34 forth herein, include required by this section.
35 (iv)(4) Include all of its terms and conditions, and be conditions.
*DRH10268-ST-8*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (v)(5) Be submitted to the secretary for his approval as to form, terms, conditions,
2 and compliance with the rules of the Commission.
3 (a3) As a minimum, the required audit report shall include the financial statements
4 prepared in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles, all disclosures in the
5 public interest required by law, and the auditor's opinion and comments relating to financial
6 statements. The audit shall be performed in conformity with generally accepted auditing
7 standards. The finance officer shall file a copy of the audit report with the secretary, and shall
8 submit all bills or claims for audit fees and costs to the secretary for his approval. Before giving
9 his approval the secretary shall determine that the audit and audit report substantially conform to
10 the requirements of this section. It shall be unlawful for any unit of local government or public
11 authority to pay or permit the payment of such the bills or claims without this approval.the
12 approval of the secretary.
13 (a4) Each officer and employee of the local government or local public authority having
14 custody of public money or responsibility for keeping records of public financial or fiscal affairs
15 shall produce all books and records requested by the auditor and shall divulge such the
16 information relating to fiscal affairs as he the auditor may request. If any member of a governing
17 board or any other public officer or employee shall conceal, falsify, or refuse to deliver or divulge
18 any books, records, or information, with an attempt thereby to mislead the auditor or impede or
19 interfere with the audit, he that individual is guilty of a Class 1 misdemeanor.
20 (b) The Local Government Commission has authority to issue rules and regulations for
21 the purpose of improving the quality of auditing and the quality and comparability of reporting
22 pursuant to this section or any similar section of the General Statutes. The rules and regulations
23 may consider the needs of the public for adequate information and the performance that the
24 auditor has demonstrated in the past, and may be varied according to the size, purpose or function
25 of the unit, or any other criteria reasonably related to the purpose or substance of the rules or
26 regulation.
27 (b1) Notwithstanding subsection (b) of this section, the State Auditor shall establish a
28 process for certified public accountants and accountants to become certified to conduct annual
29 audits under this section. Any certified public accountant or accountant certified to conduct
30 annual audits may be removed for cause.
31 (c) Notwithstanding any other provision of law, except for Article 5A of Chapter 147 of
32 the General Statutes pertaining to the State Auditor, all State departments and agencies shall rely
33 upon the single audit accepted by the secretary as the basis for compliance with applicable federal
34 and State regulations. All State departments and agencies which provide funds to local
35 governments and public authorities shall provide the Commission with documents that the
36 Commission finds are in the prescribed format describing standards of compliance and suggested
37 audit procedures sufficient to give adequate direction to independent auditors retained by local
38 governments and public authorities to conduct a single audit as required by this section. The
39 secretary shall be responsible for the annual distribution of all such standards of compliance and
40 suggested audit procedures proposed by State departments and agencies and any amendments
41 thereto. amendments. Further, the Commission with the cooperation of all affected State
42 departments and agencies shall be responsible for the following:
43 (1) Procedures for the timely distribution of compliance standards developed by
44 State departments and agencies, reviewed and approved by the Commission
45 to auditors retained by local governments and public authorities.
46 (2) Procedures for the distribution of single audits for local governments and
47 public authorities such so that they are available to all State departments and
48 agencies which provide funds to local units.
49 (3) The acceptance of single audits on behalf of all State departments and
50 agencies; provided that, the secretary may subsequently revoke such the
51 acceptance for cause, whereupon affected State departments and agencies
