1 shall no longer rely upon such the audit as the basis for compliance with
2 applicable federal and State regulations.
3 (d) Notwithstanding the requirement that the auditor is selected by and reports directly to
4 the governing board in subsection (a) subsection (a1) of this section, the Commission may require
5 the governing board of a local government or public authority that has been the subject of an
6 investigative audit with findings by the State Auditor, upon receipt of the investigative audit
7 report in accordance with G.S. 147-64.6(c)(14), to select the certified public accountant to
8 conduct the annual audit required by this section from a list of three certified public accountants
9 provided by the Commission. The Commission may instruct the Secretary secretary to issue a
10 request for proposals when selecting a certified public accountant under this subsection. Upon
11 exercise of this authority granted by this subsection, the certified public accountant auditor shall
12 report directly to the Commission and governing board, shall comply with all rules of the
13 Commission, and shall be paid by the governing board. The Commission may exercise the
14 authority granted by this subsection for up to three fiscal years after the release of the
15 investigative report with findings by the State Auditor.
16 (e) The secretary shall provide a notice of noncompliance to each county or municipality
17 unit of local government or public authority that fails to submit an annual audit report as required
18 under subsection (a) of this section within nine months of the county or municipality's fiscal year
19 end. The notice shall be sent to the governing board by first-class mail at the county or
20 municipality's to the primary mailing address. address on record with the Commission. The notice
21 shall be issued within 30 days following nine months after the county or municipality's fiscal
22 year end. A county or municipality that fails to comply with the notice of noncompliance and to
23 complete the annual audit required under subsection (a) of this section within 12 months of its
24 fiscal year end shall be deemed to have given consent to the withholding of a portion of its sales
25 tax distributions, as provided in subsection (g) of this section.
26 (f) Upon receiving a notice of noncompliance under subsection (e) of this section, a
27 county or municipality may notify the secretary in writing that it plans to appeal the action and
28 the county or municipality will be scheduled to appear before the Commission at its next
29 regularly scheduled meeting. The written notice shall state the basis for the appeal and include
30 any evidence to support the appeal. The Commission shall establish guidelines outlining specific
31 criteria that would warrant a successful appeal. If a county or municipality appeals prior to the
32 secretary taking action to withhold under subsection (g) of this section, the secretary must delay
33 withholding if the Commission determines that the county or municipality has provided sufficient
34 evidence that the failure to provide a copy of their the annual audit report required by subsection
35 (a) of this section is due to circumstances within the guidelines established by the Commission.
36 If the county or municipality appeals after the secretary takes action to withhold under subsection
37 (g) of this section, the secretary must notify the Secretary of Revenue to release any funds
38 withheld under subsection (g) of this section if the Commission determines that the county or
39 municipality has provided sufficient evidence that the failure to provide a copy of their the annual
40 audit report required by subsection (a) of this section is due to circumstances within the
41 guidelines established by the Commission.
42 (g) A county or municipality that fails to file a copy of its annual audit report as required
43 by subsection (a) of this section with the secretary within 12 months of its fiscal year end may
44 have a portion of its sales tax distributions withheld. The total cumulative amount that may be
45 withheld is an amount equal to one hundred fifty percent (150%) of the cost of the required annual
46 audit as indicated in the audit contract between the county or municipality and its external auditor
47 for the audit report, if such a contract has been executed, or one hundred fifty percent (150%) of
48 the actual fee for the most recently filed audit report if a contract has not been executed for the
49 current year audit.
50 The Secretary of Revenue must withhold from the county or municipality's distribution under
51 G.S. 105-486, and from the county or municipality's distribution under G.S. 105-501 if
