1 necessary, the amount required to be withheld upon written notification to do so from the
2 secretary. The notifications must be made on a quarterly basis. The amount to be withheld is five
3 percent (5%) of one-twelfth of the county or municipality's annual general fund budget as it was
4 adopted at the beginning of the fiscal year in which the withholding begins until the total
5 cumulative withholding amount is reached. The total cumulative amount to be withheld and any
6 schedule of withholding shall be provided by the secretary in its notification to the Secretary of
7 Revenue. The Secretary of Revenue shall begin withholding from the county or municipality's
8 first distribution of sales and use tax that is at least 45 days after they receive notification from
9 the secretary.
10 (h) When the annual audit report required under by subsection (a) of this section has been
11 filed with the secretary, reviewed to ensure compliance with the requirements of this section, and
12 accepted by the secretary or an appeal was successful under subsection (f) of this section, the
13 secretary must notify the Secretary of Revenue within 30 days to release the funds. The
14 Department of Revenue must release the funds in the county or municipality's first scheduled
15 distribution of sales tax that is at least 45 days after the earlier of the following:
16 (1) Two years from the date of notification for the funds to be withheld.
17 (2) The date the Secretary of Revenue receives notification from the secretary that
18 either (i) a report complying with the requirements of this section was filed
19 and accepted by the secretary or (ii) the county or municipality has
20 successfully appealed action taken under subsection (g) of this section.
21 (i) The secretary shall report annually to the Commission and the General Assembly a
22 list of the units of local government and public authorities failing to complete and report to the
23 Commission, in a timely fashion, two or more consecutive annual audits as required by
24 subsection (a) of this section."
25 SECTION 2.(a) G.S. 115C-447 reads as rewritten:
26 "§ 115C-447. Annual independent audit.
27 (a) Each local school administrative unit shall have its accounts and the accounts of
28 individual schools therein audited as soon as possible after the close of each fiscal year by a
29 certified public accountant or by an accountant certified by the Local Government Commission
30 State Auditor in accordance with subsection (e) of this section as qualified to audit local
31 government accounts. The auditor who audits the accounts of a local school administrative unit
32 shall also audit the accounts of its individual schools.
33 (a1) The auditor shall be selected by and shall report directly to the board of education. In
34 no instance may the governing board select an auditor not certified by the State Auditor as
35 qualified to audit local government accounts. The board of education shall solicit bids for
36 conducting the audit by sealed bid, which may be done annually but at least once every five years.
37 The board of education shall select an auditor from those sealed bids based solely on cost,
38 expertise, and time for completion of the audit and without information as to identity of the
39 bidder. If upon opening that sealed bid, the board of education determines that the auditor cannot
40 meet the audit schedule of the board of education or has performed inadequately on a prior audit
41 of the board of education, the board of education may reject that sealed bid and solicit sealed bids
42 again in accordance with this subsection.
43 (a2) The audit contract shall be in writing, shall include all its terms and conditions, and
44 shall be submitted to the Secretary secretary of the Local Government Commission for his
45 approval as to form, terms and conditions. The terms and conditions of the audit contract shall
46 include the scope of the audit, and the requirement that upon completion of the examination the
47 auditor shall prepare a typewritten or printed report embodying financial statements and his the
48 auditor's opinion and comments relating thereto.comments.
49 (a3) The financial statements accompanying the auditor's report shall be prepared in
50 conformity with generally accepted accounting principles. The auditor shall file a copy of the
51 audit report with the Secretary secretary of the Local Government Commission, the State Board
Page 4 DRH10268-ST-8

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 of Education, the board of education and the board of county commissioners, and shall submit
2 all bills or claims for audit fees and costs to the Secretary secretary of the Local Government
3 Commission for his approval. It shall be unlawful for any local school administrative unit to pay
4 or permit the payment of such the bills or claims without this approval.the approval of the
5 secretary of the Commission.
6 (a4) Each officer, employee and agent of the local school administrative unit having
7 custody of public money or responsibility for keeping records of public financial or fiscal affairs
8 shall produce all books and records requested by the auditor and shall divulge such the
9 information relating to fiscal affairs as he may request. be requested. If any member of a board
10 of education or any other public officer, employee or agent shall conceal, falsify, or refuse to
11 deliver or divulge any books, records, or information, with an intent thereby to mislead the
12 auditor or impede or interfere with the audit, he that individual is guilty of a Class 1 misdemeanor.
13 (a5) The State Auditor shall have authority to prescribe the manner in which funds
14 disbursed by administrative units by warrants on the State Treasurer shall be audited.
15 (b) When the State Board of Education finds that incidents of fraud, embezzlement, theft,
16 or management failures in a local school administrative unit make it appropriate to review the
17 internal control procedures of the unit, the State Board of Education shall so notify the unit. If
18 the incidents were discovered by the firm performing the audit under subsection (a) of this
19 section, the board of the local school administrative unit shall submit the audit together with a
20 plan for any corrective actions relative to its internal control procedures to the State Board of
21 Education and the Local Government Commission for approval and shall implement the
22 approved changes prior to the next annual audit. Where the firm preparing the audit under
23 subsection (a) of this section identifies significant problems with internal control procedures the
24 local school administrative unit shall submit the audit together with a plan for any corrective
25 actions relative to its internal control procedures to the State Board of Education and the Local
26 Government Commission for approval and shall implement the approved changes prior to the
27 next annual audit.
28 (c) If the incidents were not discovered by the firm performing the audit under subsection
29 (a) of this section, the State Board of Education and the Local Government Commission shall
30 employ an audit firm to review the internal control procedures of that local school administrative
31 unit. Upon completion of this review, the audit firm shall report publicly to the State Board of
32 Education, the Local Government Commission, and the board of the local school administrative
33 unit. If the State Board of Education determines that significant changes are needed in the internal
34 control procedures of the local school administrative unit, the local board shall submit a plan of
35 corrective actions to the State Board of Education and the Local Government Commission for
36 approval and shall implement the approved changes prior to the next annual audit. The local
37 school administrative unit shall pay the cost of this audit.
38 (d) The Commission has authority to issue rules and regulations for the purpose of
39 improving the quality of auditing and the quality and comparability of reporting pursuant to this
40 section or any similar section of the General Statutes. The rules and regulations may consider the
41 needs of the public for adequate information and the performance that the auditor has
42 demonstrated in the past and may be varied according to the size, purpose, or function of the unit,
43 or any other criteria reasonably related to the purpose or substance of the rules or regulations.
44 (e) The State Auditor shall establish a process for certified public accountants and
45 accountants to become certified to conduct annual audits under this section. Any certified public
46 accountant or accountant certified to conduct annual audits may be removed for cause.
47 (f) The secretary shall report annually to the Commission and the General Assembly a
48 list of the local school administrative units failing to complete and report to the Commission, in
49 a timely fashion, two or more consecutive annual audits as required by this section."
50 SECTION 2.(b) G.S. 115C-423 is amended by adding a new subdivision to read:
51 "(3m) "Commission" is the Local Government Commission."
